<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18440408-1339">
               <interp inst="t18440408-1339" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18440408"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18440408-1339" type="date" value="18440408"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18440408-1339-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1339-18440408 t18440408-1339-offence-1 t18440408-1339-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1336. <persName id="def1-1339-18440408" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1339-18440408" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1339-18440408" type="surname" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1339-18440408" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ANN THOMAS</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18440408-1339-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18440408-1339-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18440408-1339-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp> for feloniously and knowingly utter<lb></lb>ing counterfeit coin; having been before convicted of a like offence.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. SCRIVEN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">CHAMBERS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1689" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1689" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1689" type="surname" value="POWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1689" type="given" value="CALEB EDWARD"></interp>CALEB. EDWARD POWELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant solicitor to her Majesty's Mint. I produce a copy of the record of conviction of Ann Thomas in Oct., 1841—I have compared it with the record—it is correct—(<hi rend="italic">read</hi>,)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1690" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1690" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1690" type="surname" value="BURROWS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1690" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BURROWS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman.</hi>) I was present in this Court at the trial of Ann Thomas in 1841—the prisoner is that woman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1691" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1691" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1691" type="surname" value="WHITAKER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1691" type="given" value="JOSEPH WILLIAM"></interp>JOSEPH WILLIAM WHITAKER</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at the Noah's Ark, Park-street, South<lb></lb>wark. About a week previous to the 28th of Feb., in the afternoon, the pri<lb></lb>soner came and had a quarters of gin, and gave me a bad shilling—I ex<lb></lb>amined it, and put it on the counter, saying, "This is a bad shilling"—she immediately took it up, and put it into her mouth—I do not know whether the swallowed it or not, but I could not get it from her—I detained her for an hour and a half, could not find a policeman, and let her go—I am certain she is the woman—there was an old woman with her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long was the shilling in your possession? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Two or three minutes—the old woman went out, but I ran and prevented her—the prisoner did not offer to go—I think it was a week before the 28th of Feb.—I had a case here that day—I am satisfied of her being the person, and it was within a week of the time she was at Union-hall.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHAMBERS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You happened to be at the Police-court? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, and recognized her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1692" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1692" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1692" type="surname" value="PARTRIDGE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1692" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH PARTRIDGE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Samuel Partridge, of the White Hart. On the 28th of Feb. the prisoner came for half-a-quarters of gin with another woman—she gave me a bad shilling, which I bit, and said it was bad—the other woman gave me 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for the gin—she wanted the shilling back, and was abusive because I would not give it her—I kept it till the 11th of March in my pocket—she then came again, and my niece served her with gin, which she paid a bad shilling for—I said she was the woman who came the other day—she said, "I am certain you are mistaken, but I am positive of her—she went out directly, and my husband followed her.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184404080255"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you never see two persons exactly alike? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I am certain of her-the other woman was not a bit like her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1693" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1693" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1693" type="surname" value="SCROGGINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1693" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES SCROGGINS</persName>
                  </hi>. I was at Mr. Partridge's on the 28th of Feb.—I am certain the prisoner is the woman who had the gin and offered the bad shil-ling on the 11th of March I was in the house, and heard of a bad shilling being taken—I went out and saw the prisoner, and recognised her as having been there on the 28th of Feb.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you live in the house? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I know the first time was the 28th of Feb., as here was a funeral that day—the prisoner was in the house between six and eight minutes—I stood in front of the bat—the prisoner tendered the shilling which was refused, and the old woman paid the 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I saw her for six or seven minutes—there were two or three men there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1694" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1694" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1694" type="surname" value="NAILOR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1694" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH NAILOR</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 11th of March I was serving at my aunt's, Mrs. Partridge's, and saw the prisoner come there just before gas-light, for two-penny worth of gin—I served her—she put a bad shilling on the counter—I bit and bent it—my aunt said, "This is the same person who was here be-fore"—I went to my uncle, and he followed her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did not your aunt take charge of the shilling? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I gave it to my uncle, not to my aunt at all—I showed it to her—I am sure she did not have it and give it to my uncle.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1695" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1695" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1695" type="surname" value="PARTRIDGE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1695" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL PARTRIDGE</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 11th of March I received a shilling from my wife, and gave it to inspector Cowling—I received one the same day from my niece, and gave that to my wife—she put it into a glass behind the bar—I took it to the station—there was no other shilling in the glass—I followed the prisoner out about 100 yards, and gave her in charge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> When did you receive the shilling from your niece? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I suppose about six o'clock—I gave that shilling to my wife, and she returned it to me—I was at home on the 28th of Feb.—I got the shilling uttered on the 28th of Feb. first on the 11th of March—I took it from the glass behind the door—my wife did not keep it in her pocket till the 11th of March.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHAMBERS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did you first see the shilling uttered on the 28th of Feb.? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> On the 28th—my wife bit it and put it into the glass, and there, to the best of my belief, it remained—I believe it was still there on the 11th, when the prisoner came, but I cannot say—I put the one my niece gave me, into my pocket, and followed the prisoner—I took the other, and aimed that in my band.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1696" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1696" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1696" type="surname" value="COWLING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1696" type="given" value="JOHN RICHARD"></interp>JOHN RICHARD COWLING</persName>
                  </hi>. I received a shilling on the 11th of March from Mr. Partridge, which I produce.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Have you kept it ever since? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I made a mark on it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1697" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1697" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1697" type="surname" value="FROST"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1697" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN FROST</persName>
                  </hi>. I received a shilling from Mr. Partridge on the 11th of March, and took the prisoner in charge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1698" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1698" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1698" type="surname" value="FIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1698" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>MR. JOHN FIELD</persName>
                  </hi>. These two shillings are counterfeit.</p>
               <p>
